The movie was very bland. It's watchable because it's not some retarded woke shit, but there's nothing to watch it for.
Mthreegan has no personality and no good scenes. Her dancing scene is the one that people jerk off over but it comes out of nowhere and make no sense.
Only in at the very end she shows some kind of motive or a personality and it's just ''humanity kills people, so why can't I?'' and ''you ungrateful bitch.'' Mthreegan kills supposedly to protect the little girl who she cares very much for and the second she tries to save her adoptive mother she flips out and doesn't care about the girl at all.

The movie tries too hard to be a ''good movie'' and ''artsy.'' I hate this about modern filmmaking. Trying too hard to follow rules like show don't tell, so characters just stand around not saying anything. The little girl ends up having no personality whatsoever because 1 hour in the movie all the scenes with her are silent. All the story telling comes from people standing and looking, closeup of a character touching something, closeup to a face making a reaction to it. ''Oh look, mthreegan didn't tell the little girl to put the glass on a coaster!''
They sniff their farts so much over the filmmaking and cinematography that they forgot how to write dialogue. Without dialogue there is no chemistry between characters. We're supposed to believe the little girl loves mthreegan when mthreegan spends the entire movie just sitting there staring at her. The girl doesn't even play with mthreegan, she runs out of the house and plays alone while m4gan stands there there creepily looking from a window.
It could have been a really good movie if they had a better script with someone who knows how to write dialogue. You don't give a single fuck about any of these characters by the end of the movie. This is common for horror movies but horror movies make up with gore and cool effects, which this movie didn't have.

Maybe see if they release an R-rated cut with more violence before watching it.

YES! This is a great thing to talk about!!! I was just thinking about it after the stream.

The "Three brothers" could be read a few different ways. The clear candidates are Neteyam, Lo'ak, Payakan, and Spider. At various points in the film, there are three brothers. Initially Spider is the third brother, but then he is captured. Payakan then becomes a third brother, and there is explictly brotherly tension between Neteyam and Lo'ak as Lo'ak prefers Payakan, during which they underline the concept of brotherhood itself. Then Neteyam dies and Spider is accepted back into the family (sorta), leaving open the vague possibility of generalized brotherhood between Lo'ak, Spider and Payakan.

For me Lo'ak's personal arc is the most important hinging point in the film. He has important alone time to find his way (and is cute besides) and he is the one driving the action forward among the younger set. He is the one who takes after dad and isn't afraid to speak for himself (Neteyam is a Good Boi who takes after mom). Lo'ak is the one Seen by Tsireya and by dad afterwards.

Shit for a while there a common question directors were getting asked on talk shows and in interviews during the height of the pandemic and theatres were closing was "why should people keep going to the cinema?" and of course the directors always gave some poetic answer, when I just wanted them to scream "because that's how fucking movies are meant to be watched, you colossal assholes!" Studios don't want people going to the movies and they don't want people buying physical media because owning streaming platforms creates fewer overheads and allows them to control the films you watch more. Right now they're free to release films with shitty, rushed, and even unfinished VFX into cinemas, and then fix them for streaming and most people won't even realise there's a difference. Disney are able to reanimate scenes in their films and change the context of a moment and there is nothing you can do about it. The studios don't want people feeling a sense of ownership over a film because then they're not beholden to the past of a film.
People went fucking nuts at Lucas over the special editions and he was genuinely trying to make the films better (at least in his own mind) but with how much easier VFX are becoming and the advent of AI allowing for face replacement and voice changes, how long until the studios decide to radically alter films for their own agendas? What if Disney decides they think it's inappropriate for Jessie Ventura to say "you're all a bunch of slack-jawed faggots" in Predator and change his dialogue, and they can claim they have the right, because they "own" Fox and the Predator IP?
TL;DR - Buy physical media, and preserve films as much as possible.

Late 70s/Early 80s. But her best album Hounds of Love came out in the mid 80s. But it was like a comeback at the time, because the scene that she'd been part of had kind of faded away by then. The cultural continuity they belonged to gets severed between album releases. They probably didn't even notice the 3 - 5 years between releases, but 500 other big bands and hit songs had come thru by then. Particularly in the era these guys were active. This is sort of how they become considered "classic rock" acts, because they defied the era they came to prominence in.

You've got to think in terms of "era defining" music over-all. It's only now that we have the same ratbags shitting up the charts that we had ten years ago. Because the industry has died. The only good stuff of "now" you have to go dig up on youtube or whatever. Video games too.

It's important to me that you understand this: they each represent a different kind of rich asshole.
The Old Money, who take everything for granted.
The Wallstreet Bros, obnoxious and irreverent.
The washed-up celebrity, who sells out his art for a quick buck.
The critic who makes everything about her.
The lapdog, who enables the critic.
And finally the trustfund kid, who learns surface-level details about everything and pretends to have a profound understanding, thus cheapening it.
They are all consumers. Takers. The chef wanted them dead because of what they represent. The various culprits for the death of his art.
Also, remember that the chef isn't a good guy. He's an unhinged, obsessive sociopath. His reasoning is meant to be irregular.

>>179909792
I saw it in the cinema when it came out. My takeaway was that the chef stuff was an allegory for the director/writer and their feelings towards critics and film goers in general.
>Ralph Fiennes=Director/Writer stand-in. He wants to make simple, enjoyable food (movies) but is stuck making pretentious stuff instead.
>Nicholas Hoult=the pretentious film buff who couldn't make a good movie if he tried
>Food Critic Lady=Film Critics (no shit)
>The Rich Guy=Film Producers who constantly produce films but ultimately don't care about them, only the money that they can make from them.
>Anya Taylor Joy=The viewer who goes to see a kinda pretentious arthouse film (which The Menu apes the style of) but ultimately only wants a cheap, sloppy burger (modern spectacle based movies).
To back this up, the film has its normal spectacle movie moments like the killings at the end and the fight with the Asian lady in the cabin.
John Leguizamo was probably the most obvious allegory since he's literally playing an actor who stars in garbage and is rightly called out for it.
Overall I thought the film was like 7/10. Pretty enjoyable but nothing mind blowing.

Disagree. He provided Joel and Ellie with supplies they needed (the truck is extremely important. Using a game as source material always has the danger of producing hollow or two dimensional feeling characters in a show. But showing the history of bill, along with some glimpses into his friendship with Joel and Tess, helps give depth to the show I feel. That way you don't just have forty minute episodes of "we have to find a way to climb this wall, get these materials, get to this location, etc". Plus it served to deppen our view of Joel and Tess's relationship also. Since it shows how long they've really known each other, and the kind of marriage like dynamic they shared. Which I welcome. Her sacrifice in the previous episode lacked some emotional heft I felt; this episode helps give her absence some more weight.
